Hello again!

Well, `fallbacks()` does not modify current queryset, it returns a new one with fallbacks enabled. So your custom queryset actually does nothing more than regular TranslationQueryset.

There is no built-in way to "blanket"-add fallbacks to all querysets, because fallbacks do not work with all queries. That being said, you can make one the normal django way:

```python
class FallbackTranslationManager(TranslationManager):
    def get_queryset(self):
        return super(FallbackTranslationManager, self).get_queryset().fallbacks()
```
You'll need to add it manually to all concerned models the way you did. I would discourage you from using such a manager as the default manager though, as it violates Django rules (it may not show some objects in some circumstances).

