No, this means that you can't call `s.check` and `s.get_model()` in the order you tried to call them. You have to call `s.check()` first, and only if that check is satisfiable you're allowed to call `s.get_model()`, everything else is "invalid usage" as the exception message says. This line of code:

    cout << s.check() << endl << s.get_model() << endl;

will call `s.get_model()` first (for some compilers; the C++ standard says the order is "undefined").

